1.
Abstract Sumter County (County) is proposing an innovative recycling project using advanced municipal solid waste (MSW) composting technology to recycle two nontraditional materials universally present in the MSW stream in substantial quantities-Undeliverable Bulk Business Mail (UBBM) and small domestic animal remains.
Sumter County will conduct the project at its new state -the-art Solid Waste Facility -of in partnership with the United States Postal Service (USPS) and the Sumter County Animal Control Department.
The Sumter County Solid Waste Facility has the only operating MSW digester in Florida and is the only site that can offer the State the opportunity to evaluate these and other innovative solutions to recycling and composting problems.
The major element of the project expands existing UBBM recycling options and demonstrates the benefits of UBBM composting.
Participating USPS post offices in four communities in two counties will recover UBBM and back -haul the material to the Zephyrhills post office, a central mail distribution center for the area.
The County will collect recovered UBBM, transport the material to the Solid Waste Facility, and load UBBM directly into the County's in -vessel compost digester system without additional sorting or pre -processing.
The UBBM -content compost will be monitored and tested throughout processing to ensure quality.
When the compost is finished and screened, up to 500 cubic yards of UBBM -content compost will be made available to the USPS for landscaping and soil amendment applications.
The second element of the project involves recovering small domestic animal remains, a nontraditional material universally present in the waste stream that is not currently being recycled.
he remains of animals euthanized by the Sumter County Animal Control Department will be loaded directly into the in-vessel compost digester without pre -processing.
In the compost digester, the aerobic process pasteurizes the material, eliminating the risk of potential soil or groundwater contamination, and produces a beneficial compost product.
Because this is a nontraditional material that has not previously been recovered as compost, the proposed project includes a lab center and compost testing equipment to monitor and test the material regularly throughout processing to ensure safety and quality.
The County will establish operating procedures for handling and composting the material prepared in a form suitable for dissemination to other solid waste departments and animal control agencies.
To realize the long-term value of this project, the County proposes four education activities designed al to promote composting, and facilitate recovery of nontraditional materials, and increase recycling rates.
Sumter County will disseminate information about the project in the form of an educational brochure, a PC-compatible diskette, an educational video for general audiences and students, and a workshop for solid waste managers, recyclers, and composters.
These materials are extremely promising targets for recycling because they are universally present, easily accessible, and source separated by generators.
Since UBBM constitutes up to 90% of the USPS waste stream, this project has enormous implications and could spark the rapid development of UBBM composting programs throughout the United States.
The USPS is committed to UBBM recycling and supports this project.
