2.
Project Description Sumter County (County) is proposing an innovative recycling project using advanced technology to recycle nontraditional materials that have historically presented substantial obstacles to traditional recycling methods and operations.
The proposed project will be conducted by Sumter County at its newly-constructed Solid Waste Facility, a state -the-art integrated recycling and composting facility -of that combines a front-end materials recovery facility with an in -vessel compost digester system.
The Sumter County Solid Waste Facility has the only operating municipal solid waste (MSW) digester in Florida and is the only site that can offer the State the opportunity to evaluate these and other innovative solutions to recycling and composting problems.
The proposed project will make an important contribution to Florida recycling practices by expanding MSW recycling operations to include two nontraditional materials that are universally present but currently not being recovered by traditional recycling technologies.
This project represents a regional approach to developing innovative recycling solutions.
The project is an individual County project, but the largest element of the project will be carried out by the County in partnership with the United States Postal Service (USPS) with the participation of USPS service facilities located in five separate communities in Hillsborough and Pasco Counties.
The project will demonstrate the environmental and economic benefits of recycling two nontraditional materials.
The major element of the project entails the recovery of Undeliverable Bulk Business Mail (UBBM) through composting to produce Class A compost.
The second element of the project will demonstrate the benefits of recovering small domestic animal remains from the municipal solid waste stream, and the third element will disseminate information about the project and its results.
The three elements of the project are described in more detail in the following subsections.
Element #1: Composting Undeliverable Bulk Business Mail The major element of the project expands existing UBBM recycling options and demonstrates the benefits of UBBM composting.
(See Section3, Advanced Technologies or Processes,for a detailed discussion of existing recycling options.).
The County proposes to collect UBBM generated by post offices located in Zephyrhills, Dade City, Land O'Lakes, Lutz, and Odessa, Florida.
Participating USPS service facilities will recover UBBM and back -haul the material to the Zephyrhills Post Office, a central mail processing plant for the area.
Sumter County will collect the material at the Zephyrhills Post Office and transport it to the County's Solid Waste Facility where the material will be loaded directly into the County's enclosed compost digester without additional sorting or processing.
Following initial processing in the digester, partially composted material will be transferred to a finishing area for final "curing" and finishing.
The UBBM project is designed to take full advantage of existing USPS infrastructure and resources.
Specifically, the Zephyrhills facility is a central processing plant that processes mail SC21/InnGrant. doc
SUMTER COUNTY TIN 59-6000865 RFP NO. 9808C INNO VA TI VE RECYCLING PROJECTS ___________________________________________________________________________________ 2.
Project Description (con't) coming into the area and distributes it to local post offices in Dade City, Land O'Lakes, Lutz, and Odessa for final sorting and delivery to recipients.
Each day, USPS mail trucks are loaded at the Zephyrhills facility, transport mail to the four post offices, and return empty to the Zephyrhills plant.
This in-place transportation system offers a cost -effective and efficient means for "back -hauling" UBBM to the Zephyrhills plant for collection and processing.
(See Section 5, Cost Effectiveness, for a detailed cost analysis of this project element.)
To implement UBBM recycling, each participating USPS facility will be provided with covered, wheeled containers suitable for storing recovered UBBM.
As part of daily operations, USPS staff will deposit recovered UBBM in these containers, and filled containers will be loaded onto empty USPS trucks returning to the Zephyrhills plant.
At the Zephyrhills plant, containers will be removed from trucks and emptied into covered roll containers for temporary storage.
Empty wheeled containers -off will be returned to participating USPS facilities via outgoing mail trucks from the Zephyrhills facility.
As frequently as necessary, Sumter County will collect roll containers and transport the material to -off the Sumter County Solid Waste Facility.
At the facility, the material will be unloaded directly from roll off containers by means of a front -loader into an in-feed hopper and onto a direct -feed conveyor for input into the County's compost digester without further processing or sorting.
Processed MSW will also be added to the digester, along with the appropriate quantities of nitrogen source material and water required to support the aerobic composting process.
Oxygen levels, temperature readings, and moisture content will be monitored and adjusted throughout the process to ensure optimal conditions for decomposition.
A lab center and compost testing equipment is included in the project to support testing activities scheduled throughout the compost production process.
After processing in the digester for approximately three days, partially composted material is discharged, screened, and deposited in windrows in the compost finishing area, an enclosed area where compost is protected from exposure to weather and excessive moisture.
In the finishing area, turning machines periodically agitate and aerate the compost to complete the composting process and produce the best quality compost.
After finishing, compost will undergo a final screening before distribution for standard composting applications.
As part of the project, Sumter County will provide the USPS with up to 500 cubic yards of UBBM-content compost for use in landscaping and soil amen dment applications.
The County will also cooperate with the USPS to develop procurement specifications for UBBM -content compost to facilitate procurement and expand markets for the product.
This portion of the project is particularly important to the long-term transferability of this element of the project since the USPS is committed to developing "closed-loop" recycling programs for UBBM.
(See Section Technology Transfer,for a 4, more detailed discussion of the project's transferability.)
