2.
Project Description (con't) recycled.
Historically, disposal options for animal remains have been limited to incineration and burial.
Florida regulations [Section 823.041(1), F.S.] require animal owners and custodians to dispose of the carcasses of diseased animals by burning or burial at least two (2) feet below the surface but impose no restrictions on public disposal technologies.
Regulations do not require that these remains be disposed of in Class I landfills or in lined excavations to eliminate the risk of ground water contamination.
Further, regulations do not address the disposal of healthy, humanely euthanized animals.
(See Section 3,Advanced Technologies or Processesfor a discussion of current practices.)
The County proposes to demonstrate the advantages of in -vessel composting to recover a beneficial product from this material.
The County's Animal Control Department is located adjacent to the County Solid Waste Facility.
Received or impounded small domestic animals that are not claimed or adopted are routinely euthanized at the Animal Control facility.
During the proposed project, animal remains will be transported to the Solid Waste Facility by means of a front -loader, loaded into an in -feed hopper, and input into the compost digester by a direct -feed conveyor.
Processed MSW will also be added to the digester, along with the appropriate quantities of nitrogen source material and water required to support the aerobic composting process.
In the compost digester, the aerobic process pasteurizes the material, eliminating the risk of potential soil or groundwater contamination, and produces a beneficial compost product.
(See Section Cost 5, Effectiveness, for a discussion of the economic benefits associated with the proposed innovative technology.)
After processing in the digester for approximately three days, the partially composted material will be discharged and handled following the procedures described in Element #1: Composting Undeliverable Bulk Business Mailbefore being distributed for use in Sumter County public works projects.
Because this is a nontraditional material that has not previously been recovered as compost, the proposed project includes a lab center and compost testing equipment to monitor and test the material regularly throughout processing to ensure that optimal oxygen, nitrogen, and moisture levels are maintained.
Compost produced using this material will be inspected and carefully evaluated to document the quality of the finished compost product and its suitability for standard applications.
The project will establish operating procedures for handling and composting the material prepared in a form suitable for dissemination to other solid waste managers and animal control agencies in Florida.
(See Section 4, Technology Transfer,for a discussion of the transferability of the project's innovative technology.)
Element #3: Public Education and Information Dissemination Sumter County is proud of its new Solid Waste Facility and is confident that this project will make an important contribution to MSW recycling operations in Florida.
To realize the potential long -term value of this project, Sumter County is prepared to commit substantial efforts to public education and information dissemination.
The Sumter County Solid Waste Facility attracts large numbers of visitors each year and hosts tours by state, regional, national, and international
