The facility is recognized for its state -the art technology, and it serves as an -of appropriate site for promoting innovative technologies.
In addition to making one formal presentation about the project at an appropriate state or national workshop within one year following completion of the project, the County proposes four additional educational activities designed to promote composting and facilitate recovery of materials not presently being recovered from the MSW stream.
The following subsections describe the public education and information dissemination activities the County proposes in connection with this innovative recycling project.
Educational Brochure: Sumter County will develop and produce an educational brochure describing MSW recycling and composting operations at the Sumter County Solid Waste Facility for distribution to visitors to the facility and by mail to other Florida solid waste departments.
The brochure will particularly focus on expanding MSW composting to nontraditional materials and will include a description of the County's UBBM and small domestic animal remains projects.
Educational Diskette: Sumter County will develop and produce a PC -compatible diskette presenting information about MSW recycling and composting.
Information will include lessons learned from the County's more than ten years experience with MSW composting, documentation of the benefits of MSW composting, and guidelines for MSW compost marketing.
The diskette will be available on request at no charge.
Educational Video: Sumter County will develop and produce an educational video suitable for general audiences and students.
The video will explain MSW composting, describe the benefits of this technology, and promote the use of MSW compost as a high quality soil amendment.
The video will be used to supplement visitors' tours of the facility and will be available to community groups and schools for educational and classroom use at no charge.
Educational Workshop: In cooperation with the Florida Organics Recyclers Association, Sumter County will conduct an educational workshop for municipal and private solid waste managers, recyclers, and composters at the Solid Waste Facility.
The workshop will include a tour of the facility, a presentation on MSW composting, and a discussion of composting nontraditional materials to increase recycling rates.
