3.
Advanced Technologies or Processes Currently, the USPS is energetically promoting UBBM recycling to capitalize on the economic, environmental, and customer satisfaction benefits associated with recovering this material.
The USPS is particularly interested in developing "closed -loop" recycling programs that produce UBBM -content products the Postal Service can use in routine operations.
While recovery and collection of UBBM is relatively easy to accomplish by using existing USPS fleet transportation systems to "back -haul" material to a central location, the USPS has had difficulty finding markets for recovered UBBM.
The lack of markets has curtailed recycling efforts, and large quantities of UBBM presently enter the MSW stream for disposal.
If adequate recycling markets were available, the USPS could recover virtually all of this material.
UBBM presents problems for conventional recycling technologies.
The material, if it is recognized as recyclable, is classified as "low -grade mixed paper" in commodity markets.
Unlike other mixed paper, contamination from adhesives [also known as pressure sensitive adhesives (PSAs) or "stickles"], window envelopes, and glossy paper renders UBBM unacceptable for conventional paper recycling operations, which require more homogeneous feedstocks.
Even though the USPS has been able to find limited recovery partners in Chicago and Atlanta, large metropolitan areas with established, specialized recycled paper mills, UBBM quantities far exceed the recycled paper industry's capacity.
Low market values and high transportation costs prohibit widespread UBBM recycling.
In an aggressive effort to develop recycling alternatives for UBBM, the USPS has developed innovative projects with Gridcore, Inc. of Long Beach, California to manufacture UBBM -content recycling containers for post offices, with J. R. Moon Pencil Co., in Lewisburg, Tennessee to manufacture pencils that contain 25% recycled UBBM, and with Pure Vision Technologies in Denver, Colorado to examine the feasibility of transforming UBBM into ethanol.
While these projects demonstrate alternate uses for recovered UBBM, none of these technologies have proved economically viable for processing available large quantities of UBBM.
In January 1997, the USPS funded an innovative composting pilot project by Texas A 
The project, the first of its kind in the country, composted shredded UBBM in an outdoor windrow along with yard trimmings, liquid wastes, grocery and food processing residues, and approximately 250 cubic yards of wood chips.
The compost, which took four months to produce, is now being tested in horticultural applications by Texas A 
In comparison to the Texas pilot project, the potential impact of the County's project is enormous.
The County's project can potentially create a virtually unlimited market for UBBM in Florida and nationally.
Relying on its extensive experience with MSW composting and its state -the-art -of composting technology, the County proposes to demonstrate the viability of using UBBM feedstock in MSW composting, an innovative but accessible technology with the capacity to recycle large quantities of UBBM to produce a valuable marketable product with many marketing options.
Compared with traditional paper recycling options, composting technology is readily available, relatively inexpensive, SC21/InnGrant.doc
