The Sumter County project alone could potentially more than double the quantities of UBBM being recovered and could recycle virtually 100% of the UBBM being generated by the Zephyrhills service area.
The Zephyrhills Post Office presently generates approximately 14 tons per month of material, and the Lutz Post Office generates approximately 7 tons per month.
(Under current service arrangements, the USPS has no assurance that this material is being recycled since local commercial recyclers who collect UBBM may dispose of the material if a market is not available.)
UBBM is not currently being recovered at the Dade City, Odessa, and Land O'Lakes facilities.
The second element of the County's project also involves a material that is not currently being recycled.
While no State-wide or national data is available, the County has found no information that suggests that small domestic animals remains are being recycled for beneficial use in any county in Florida.
Prevalent disposal technologies, burial and burning, present potential difficulties, result in adverse environmental impacts, and produce no beneficial products.
(See Section 5, Cost Effectiveness, for the discussion of the economic benefits of recycling this material.)
Understandably, the nature of this material tends to discourage public discussion of current disposal practices and community involvement in planning for material management.
Inside the solid waste industry, the material is rarely discussed.
Consequently, animal control agencies and solid waste planners have had little incentive to develop alternative technologies.
The project proposed by the County will demonstrate the benefits of composting this material and will develop material handling procedures and composting guidelines for use by other counties.
A preliminary project survey indicates that the five counties in the Sumter County area use either incineration or landfill disposal for managing small domestic animal remains.
Those counties that burn animal remains transport ashes to local landfills or to waste -energy facilities for disposal.
Counties -to that do not operate crematories, transport remains directly to landfills for disposal.
None of the counties surveyed recover any beneficial use from the material.
Many small counties in Florida, like Sumter County, do not operate landfills and do not generate sufficient quantities of the material to justify incineration equipment.
Counties that do not operate landfills or crematories must dispose of animal remains by burial, a disposal method that produces no beneficial products, presents material handling problems, and poses potential risks associated with disposal in unlined excavations.
For large counties that generate substantial quantities of material, composting offers the opportunity to divert material from landfills, eliminate landfill or waste-to-energy tip fees, and produce a beneficial product.
The County's project presents unique opportunities to increase Florida's MSW recycling rates by recovering two organic materials that are not currently being recovered.
Composting technology is ideally suited to both UBBM and small domestic animal remains.
