5.
Cost Effectiveness The County's project will demonstrate that composting is an economically viable and cost effective alternative to existing recycling and disposal options for both UBBM and small domestic animal remains.
Over 80% of the project budget is earmarked for recycling infrastructure with a useful life of 10 to 15 years.
This infrastructure will allow the County to not only to continue to recycle the two nontraditional materials included in this project but also to expand MSW composting in the future to other nontraditional materials that can be direct -fed into the County's digester.
Thus, while the costs of the project will be substantially recovered in the next few years, the project will produce benefits for many years to come.
Because neither UBBM nor small domestic animal remains is currently being recycled, statewide average recycling costs are not available.
Currently, UBBM recycling is extremely limited, and UBBM that is not separately recovered is collected and disposed of as Class I solid waste.
A preliminary project survey indicates that small domestic animal remains are not presently being recovered for beneficial use.
Thus, a portion of project costs will be recovered through avoidance of $50 to $70 per ton disposal costs and production of a beneficial product with a market value of approximately $20 per ton.
Under existing recycling service arrangements, recovered UBBM is collected at individual USPS service locations by local recyclers.
These local recyclers may be able to market limited amounts of UBBM by tying the material to more desirable commodities such as OCC or ONP.
This marketing strategy devalues higher quality commodities and creates market problems by forcing acceptance of UBBM.
End-users forced to accept UBBM in order to get better products eventually dispose of large quantities of unusable UBBM at landfills.
Even if recyclers can market limited quantities of UBBM by combining UBBM with more valuable commodities, they would be unable to market the quantity of material that would be generated by a fully -committed UBBM recycling program.
In addition to limiting the quantity of UBBM that can be recovered, current recycling arrangements impose other limitations.
Because UBBM is difficult to market to traditional recycled paper markets, local recyclers must charge the USPS premium rates for collecting, transporting and marketing or disposing of the material if unmarketable.
Under these arrangements, the USPS has no opportunity to offset transportation costs by taking advantage of USPS truck fleets to back -haul material to a central collection site.
Moreover, once UBBM is collected by local recyclers, the USPS has no guarantee that it will not be disposed of if unmarketable and no opportunity to procure UBBM -content products.
Project participants that currently recycle pay a minimum of $30 per ton plus $100 per pickup for recycling service.
The County anticipates that UBBM composting can reduce those costs by more than half.
The proposed UBBM project will improve cost -effectiveness in four ways: * * Reducing transportation and handling costs Eliminating preprocessing expenses
