5.
Cost Effectiveness (con't) * * Producing a valuable UBBM -content end-product Reducing undesirable environmental impacts
The County's project will improve cost effectiveness by reducing transportation and handling costs in several ways.
First, by using empty USPS trucks to back -haul material to a central collection site, the project eliminates a substantial portion of transportation costs for collection.
Second, by collecting the material in roll-off containers at a central location, the project maximizes economies of scale and reduces material handling costs.
Finally, the project eliminates marketing costs by processing the material locally rather than transporting it long distances to major recycled paper markets with the hope that some portion may be recyclable.
The County's project also eliminates the need for expensive pre -processing.
Recovered UBBM be loaded directly from roll-off storage into the County's compost digester witho additional sorting or ut pre-processing.
Unlike the recycled paper manufacturing process, this innovative composting technology eliminates the need to sort, compact, bale, wash, bleach, chemically treat, or otherwise pre-process the material to prepare it for recycling.
The County's project will produce a viable UBBM -content end product suitable for procurement by the USPS.
The County has been producing MSW compost for more than ten years and during that time has used MSW compost in a variety of landscaping and public works applications.
Based on this extensive experience, the County anticipates that the use of MSW compost will result in substantial savings and produce superior results compared with top soil and other soil amendments.
In the case of small domestic animal remains, the County's project is expected to improve cost effectiveness by reducing labor costs for material handling and by producing a valuable end product from material that is not presently being recovered.
(Communities where the material or ash residue are landfilled could expect to achieve additional substantial savings from disposal cost avoidance.)
Finally, for every ton of UBBM that is back -hauled and every ton of animal remains that are composted, environmental impacts are reduced.
Composting these materials conserves valuable resources by reducing fuel, tire, and vehicle consumption and decreasing wear on roads highways.
Composting reduces energy consumption in processing and diverts material from landfills.
Moreover, "closed-loop" recycling continues to be one of the most environmentally desirable recycling options.
While composting these materials is a cost -effective alternative for Sumter County, the long- term benefit of the project is its greater value as a demonstration for other Florida communities.
The County's project will demonstrate that composting is an economically viable, environmentally sound alternative to traditional recycling technology that can help Florida increase recycling rates by expanding MSW and yard waste composting to include these and other nontraditional materials SC21/InnGrant.doc
