6.
Nontraditional Materials The County proposes to collect and recycle two nontraditional materials, UBBM and small domestic animal remains.
Both materials satisfy the definition of MSW specified in Section 403.706(5), F.S., which includes "any solid waste, except for sludge, resulting from the operation of residential, commercial, governmental, or institutional establishments that would normally be collected, processed, and disposed of through a public or private solid waste management service."
Both UBBM and small domestic animal remains are generated by government agencies (the USPS and Sumter County Animal Control, respectively) and are normally disposed of as solid waste.
UBBM is an attractive target material for innovative recycling technologies.
By definition, UBBM is a unique material generated in large quantities by USPS mail facilities throughout Florida and the United States.
UBBM, which constitutes up to 90% of the agency's waste stream, is segregated from other mail and solid waste as part of normal USPS operations, and, thus, the material is relatively easy to recover at its source.
Because of the material's high generation rates and ease of separation, the USPS is highly motivated to recover the material.
To facilitate UBBM recycling, the USPS is willing to use its in -place transportation system to back -haul material to USPS mail processing centers for centralized collection.
In addition, the USPS also promotes "closed -loop" recycling and would support end market development by procuring UBBM -content products.
UBBM, which is generally classified as "low -grade mixed paper" in commodity markets, contains high levels of contaminants such as adhesive, window envelops, and glossy papers that render the material unsuitable for conventional paper recycling technologies.
Consequently, traditional paper markets are not available to process the quantities of UBBM that can potentially be recovered.
Until an innovative technology is developed to provide a stable and expandable market for UBBM, the material can not be recycled.
Small domestic animal remains constitute a material present in Florida's MSW stream that is not currently being recycled.
Like UBBM, this material is unique and is generated solely by privately practicing veterinarians and government or quasi -governmental agencies.
It is segregated at its source and can be easily diverted from the MSW stream.
The most prevalent current disposal methods are burning and burial, neither of which permits beneficial use of the material.
Because animal remains present potential human health risks and unique aesthetic considerations, this material is not suitable for traditional recycling technologies.
At the same time, the nature of the material tends to discourage public discussion of material management options, and solid waste managers and animal control agencies have had little incentive to develop alternative technologies.
Both UBBM and small domestic animal remains constitute suitable organic feedstocks for MWS composting Composting technologies are flexible and accessible enough to provide a stable and SC21/InnGrant.doc
