Nontraditional Materials (con't) expandable processing market for virtually unlimited quantities of UBBM.
In -vessel composting systems, which are available in a wide range of capacities, are an aesthetically and biologically acceptable recycling option for recycling animal remains.
While yard waste composting and mulching operations have proliferated in Florida since landfill disposal was prohibited and yard waste composting was deregulated, MSW composting remains an advanced technology.
Composting is an increasingly attractive alternative given Florida's projected stagnating diversion rates.
Now that the State has achieved a 37% recycling rate, the rate of increase has leveled and is not expected to keep pace with steadily increasing generation rates and population growth.
In these circumstances, organic fractions are a promising target for recyclers.
Organics account for over 50% of Florida's MSW stream, and paper alone makes up nearly 30%.
Even disregarding OCC, NOP, and office paper, other lower grades of paper make up over 10% of Florida's MSW stream.
Thus, in addition to providing a stable market for UBBM and small animal remains, the project's technology offers an attractive innovative alternative for recovering materials with limited recycling options.
The project's UBBM collection system also represents a nontraditional approach to recycling.
By taking advantage of existing USPS infrastructure, the County is able to dramatically improve cost effectiveness and reduce recycling costs.
By reducing recycling costs below disposal costs, the project creates the necessary economic incentives for generators to increase recovery rates to achieve virtually 100% recovery of available material.
The County's regional approach is another nontraditional feature.
This project represents an innovative partnership between a federal agency, a local animal control department, and a county solid waste facility to provide service at sites in six separate communities in three counties.
The project is exceptionally flexible and can be easily expanded to incorporated additional USPS facilities located in the area.
In sum, the County's project involves the recovery of two nontraditional materials by means of an innovative composting technology.
The project's potential benefits are enormous.
This project can serve as a useful demonstration of the advantages of MSW and yard waste composting and a valuable lesson in how recycling rates can be substantially increased by expanding MSW and yard waste composting to nontraditional materials.
While UBBM and small domestic animal remains were selected for this project because of their easy accessibility and high generation rates, the project's innovative technology is directly applicable to other organic fractions in Florida's MSW stream.
This project's innovative technology is highly transferable, easily adapted to other nontraditional materials, and flexible enough to suit a variety of applications and contexts.
Small rural counties and large metropolitan areas will benefit from the project's exciting results and impressive potential for increasing recycling rates.
